 Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["French: from a diminutive of Old French <i>bas(se)</i> ‘short, of low stature’ (see   Bas  ).","English: variant of   Bassett  , a cognate of 1 above.","In some cases also an altered form of French <b>Besset</b> (see   Bessette   2). Compare   Bassette   1."],"variants":[{"name":"Bas","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Mauricio, Abelardo, Florencio, Francisco, Jorge, Luis, Manuel, Pedro, Soledad, Vicente.  Eastern Slavic Dmytro, Liya, Pyotr, Sergey.","Catalan: habitational name from a place so named in the district of La Garrotxa, Catalonia.","Basque: topographic name for someone who lived by a wood, from <i>baso</i> ‘wood, forest’."]}]},{"name":"Elizabeth","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["The usual spelling of   Elisabeth   in English. It is recorded in the medieval period, but was made popular by being borne by  Queen Elizabeth I  of England (  1533–1603 ). In the 20th century it again became extremely fashionable, partly because it was the name of  Elizabeth Bowes-Lyon  (  1900–2002 ), who in  1936  became Queen Elizabeth as the wife of King George VI, and after his death in  1952  achieved great public affection as Queen Mother for nearly half a century. Even more influentially, it is the name of her daughter  Queen Elizabeth II  (  b. 1926 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Elisabeth","meanings":["The spelling of   Elizabeth   used in the Authorized Version of the New Testament, and in most modern European languages. This was the name of the mother of John the Baptist (Luke 1:60). Etymologically, the name means ‘God is my oath’, and is therefore identical with <i>Elisheba</i>, the name of the wife of Aaron according to the genealogy at Exodus 6:23. The final element seems to have been altered by association with Hebrew <i>shabbāth</i> ‘Sabbath’."]}]},{"name":"Cecilia","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From the Latin name <i>Caecilia</i>, feminine form of <i>Caecilius</i> (  see  Cecil  ). This was a good deal more common than the masculine form, largely due to the fame of the 2nd- or 3rd-century virgin martyr whose name is still mentioned daily in the Roman Catholic Canon of the Mass. She is regarded as the patron saint of music and has inspired works such as  Purcell's  ‘Ode on St Cecilia's Day’, although the reasons for this association are not clear."],"variants":[{"name":"Cecelia","meanings":["From the Latin name <i>Caecilia</i>, feminine form of <i>Caecilius</i> (  see  Cecil  ). This was a good deal more common than the masculine form, largely due to the fame of the 2nd- or 3rd-century virgin martyr whose name is still mentioned daily in the Roman Catholic Canon of the Mass. She is regarded as the patron saint of music and has inspired works such as  Purcell's  ‘Ode on St Cecilia's Day’, although the reasons for this association are not clear."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Lady Elizabeth Cecilia Basset was born in 1395, in Blore, Staffordshire, England as the daughter of William Basset, of Blore. She married Sir John Beresforde in 1410, in Derbyshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 5 sons. She died in 1420, in England, United Kingdom, at the age of 25."},"et":{"1395–1420":"1395–1420","1380–1473":"1380–1473","1411–1475":"1411–1475","1417–1448":"1417–1448","1420–1473":"1420–1473","1425–Male":"1425–Surnud","1426–Male":"1426–Surnud","1416–Male":"1416–Surnud","1473":"1473","1395":"1395","1380":"1380","1426":"1426","1448":"1448","1425":"1425","about 1417":"umbes 1417","1411":"1411","1410":"1410","1420":"1420","1475":"1475","about 1411":"umbes 1411","1417":"1417","1416":"1416","Derbyshire, England, United Kingdom":"Derbyshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Blore, Staffordshire, England":"Blore, Staffordshire, England"},"fi":{"1395–1